\b PW Internship \u2014 Screening Assignment\b0\par
\par
\b Task 01 Automated Annotation System\b0\par
\par
\b WHAT TO SUBMIT\b0\par
\par
1. The output video showing annotations appearing on the background, synced with the audio.\par
\par
- Local output: output/final.mp4\par
- Example placeholder link: https://example.com/final.mp4\par
\par
2. Your tool or process:\par
\par
- Repository / scripts: scripts/generateAnnotations.py, scripts/renderVideo.py, scripts/ocrQuestion.py, scripts/renameQuestions.py, main.py\par
- Screen recording (or demo): Automated Annotation System final video.mp4 (upload if required)\par
\par
\b How the tool works (short):\b0\par
\par
- Input: question image (input/*.png) and narration audio (input/*.mp3).\par
- Steps:\par
  - (optional) Transcribe audio with Whisper → output/transcript.json (word and segment timestamps).\par
  - OCR question image with EasyOCR → extract question text, options, and bounding boxes.\par
  - generateAnnotations.py parses the OCR text and transcript to create an 8-action annotation schedule (two write_text, five write_equation, one tick_answer). The generator auto-detects problem type (distance, kinematics, generic) and populates content accordingly.\par
  - renderVideo.py consumes output/annotations.json and renders handwriting-style progressive annotations into output/final.mp4.\par
\par
- Key improvements made for the submission:\par
  - Dynamic content: coordinates or equation steps are extracted from OCR and transcript text (distance and kinematics supported).\par
  - Smart sync: annotation timestamps are aligned to transcript words/segments (word-level when available) and include a small positive offset so visuals appear just after speech.\par
  - Stable demo structure: 8 actions preserved so output matches original demo timing/flow while being dynamic.\par
\par
\b How to run (quick):\b0\par
\par
{\f1\qc\lang1033\par}
\f0
\pard\tx360
\par
1) optional: create transcript\par
\f1
python main.py --image input/question.png --audio input/narration.mp3\par
\f0
\par
2) or skip transcription if transcript.json exists\par
\f1
python main.py --image input/question.png --audio input/narration.mp3 --skip-transcribe\par
\f0
\par
\b Notes on reproducibility\b0\par
\par
- The pipeline expects input/ files and writes output/transcript.json, output/annotations.json, and output/final.mp4.\par
- If transcripts include per-word timestamps, the sync is tighter. Otherwise it falls back to segment matching plus heuristics.\par
\par
\b Task 02 Brief an AI to Write in Your Voice\b0\par
\par
Subject Choice & Context\par
\par
- Subject: Database Management Systems (DBMS)\par
- Exam Context: B.Tech Semester Final Examination\par
- Reason: Balanced familiarity—good representation of typical performance.\par
\par
\b Brief for the AI (deliverable)\b0\par
\par
You are attempting a DBMS final exam as if you were me.\par
\par
\b Knowledge Level\b0\par
\par
- Strong: Database fundamentals, ER Diagrams, Keys & Constraints, SQL Queries, Normalization up to 3NF, Transactions and ACID, Joins and Relationships.\par
- Weaker: Query optimization, index internals, distributed DBs, advanced concurrency control.\par
\par
\b Writing Style & Answer Structure\b0\par
\par
- Simple English, clear explanations, start with a definition then explain, use examples, end with a brief conclusion.\par
- For theory: definition → explanation → example → conclusion.\par
- For SQL: show query first, minimal explanation.\par
- For comparisons: use concise bullet lists or tables (4–6 differences).\par
\par
\b Sample short AI brief (copyable):\b0\par
\par
"You are answering a B.Tech final exam in DBMS as if you were a mid-level student. Use simple English, start answers with a definition, follow with a brief explanation and an example, and end with a short conclusion. Prioritize clarity over depth. For SQL questions, present the query first. Avoid advanced jargon."\par
\par
\b What Would the AI Still Get Wrong About Me?\b0\par
\par
- The AI will likely be more consistent than my real exam performance; it may not reproduce occasional dropped details or the small mistakes I make under time pressure.\par
\par
\b Task 03 Fix a Broken Workflow\b0\par
\par
What Was Broken\par
\par
- Excel had mapping between question numbers and randomly-named images in ZIP files. No reliable automated mapping existed, so employees manually matched and screenshot.\par
\par
My Solution (script)\par
\par
- Script: scripts/renameQuestions.py (see repo). Steps:\par
  1. Read Excel metadata (auto-detect columns: filename, file_name, image, attachment, question_no, question_number, sr_no).\par
  2. Extract images from ZIP, ignore macOS artifacts.\par
  3. Match images to metadata by filename heuristics.\par
  4. Rename images to Q1.png, Q2.png, S1.png, S2.png and handle duplicates.\par
\par
Edge cases handled: column variations, missing numbers (sequential fallback), unknown types (warning), duplicate names (suffix), multiple image formats.\par
\par
Possible Improvements\par
\par
- Support nested ZIP folders, add --dry-run, GUI, PDF page extraction, and detailed audit logs.\par
\par
Files created/modified for this assignment\par
\par
- main.py — pipeline runner and CLI\par
- scripts/generateAnnotations.py — annotation generator (rule-based + heuristics)\par
- scripts/renderVideo.py — renderer\par
- scripts/ocrQuestion.py — OCR helper\par
- scripts/renameQuestions.py — workflow fixer\par
\par
Contact / Notes\par
\par
- If you want, I can produce a short screen recording showing the run and open the generated output/final.mp4 for upload.\par
